.TH "ELEMENT.OUTERHTML" "3JS" "November 21, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Element.outerHTML \- Element: outerHTML property
.SH SYNOPSIS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] This property parses its input as HTML, writing the
result into the DOM.
APIs like this are known as injection sinks, and are potentially a
vector for cross\-site scripting (XSS) attacks, if the input originally
came from an attacker.
.PP
You can mitigate this risk by always assigning \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
objects instead of strings and enforcing trusted types.
See Security considerations for more information.
.RE
.PP
The \f[B]\f[CB]outerHTML\f[B]\f[R] attribute of the \f[CR]Element\f[R]
interface gets or sets the HTML or XML markup of the element and its
descendants, omitting any shadow roots in both cases.
.PP
To get or set the contents of an element, use the \f[CR]innerHTML\f[R]
property instead.
.SH VALUE
Getting the property returns a string containing an HTML serialization
of the \f[CR]element\f[R] and its descendants.
.PP
Setting the property accepts either a \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] object or a
string.
The input is parsed as HTML and replaces the element and all its
descendants with the result.
When set to the \f[CR]null\f[R] value, that \f[CR]null\f[R] value is
converted to the empty string (\f[CR]\(dq\(dq\f[R]), so
\f[CR]element.outerHTML = null\f[R] is equivalent to
\f[CR]element.outerHTML = \(dq\(dq\f[R].
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]NoModificationAllowedError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if an attempt was made to set \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] on an element
which is a direct child of a \f[CR]Document\f[R], such as
\f[CR]Document.documentElement\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]SyntaxError\f[R] \f[B]DOMException\f[R]
Thrown if an attempt was made to set \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] using an XML
input which is not well\-formed.
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if the property is set to a string when Trusted Types are
enforced by a CSP and no default policy is defined.
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] gets a serialization of the element, or sets HTML
or XML that should be parsed to replace it within the element\(cqs
parent.
.PP
If the element has no parent node, setting its \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R]
property will not change it or its descendants.
For example:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] div = document.createElement(\(dqdiv\(dq);
div.outerHTML = \(aq<div class=\(dqtest\(dq>test</div>\(aq;
console.log(div.outerHTML); \f[I]// output: \(dq<div></div>\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
Also, while the element will be replaced in the document, the variable
whose \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] property was set will still hold a reference
to the original element:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] p = document.querySelector(\(dqp\(dq);
console.log(p.nodeName); \f[I]// shows: \(dqP\(dq\f[R]
p.outerHTML = \(dq<div>This div replaced a paragraph.</div>\(dq;
console.log(p.nodeName); \f[I]// still \(dqP\(dq;\f[R]
.EE
.SS Escaped attribute values
The returned value will escape some values in HTML attributes.
Here we see that the \f[CR]&\f[R] character is escaped:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] anchor = document.createElement(\(dqa\(dq);
anchor.href = \(dqhttps://developer.mozilla.org?a=b&c=d\(dq;
console.log(anchor.outerHTML); \f[I]// output: \(dq<a href=\(aqhttps://developer.mozilla.org?a=b&amp;c=d\(aq></a>\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.PP
Some browsers also serialize the \f[CR]<\f[R] and \f[CR]>\f[R]
characters as \f[CR]&lt;\f[R] and \f[CR]&gt;\f[R] when they appear in
attribute values (see Browser compatibility).
This is to prevent a potential security vulnerability (\c
.UR https://www.securitum.com/mutation-xss-via-mathml-mutation-dompurify-2-0-17-bypass.html
mutation XSS
.UE \c
) in which an attacker can craft input that bypasses a sanitization
function, enabling a cross\-site scripting (XSS) attack.
.SS Shadow DOM considerations
The serialization of the DOM tree read from the property does not
include shadow roots.
If you want to get an HTML serialization of an element that includes
shadow roots, you must instead use the \f[CR]Element.getHTML()\f[R]
method.
Note that this gets the \f[I]contents\f[R] of the element.
.PP
Similarly, when setting element content using \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R], the
HTML input is parsed into DOM elements that do not contain shadow roots.
So for example \f[CR]<template>\f[R] is parsed into as
\f[CR]HTMLTemplateElement\f[R], whether or not the
\f[CR]shadowrootmode\f[R] attribute is specified.
If you want to set an element\(cqs \f[I]contents\f[R] from an HTML input
that includes declarative shadow roots, you must instead use
\f[CR]Element.setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R] or
\f[CR]ShadowRoot.setHTMLUnsafe()\f[R].
.SS Security considerations
The \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] property is possible vector for cross\-site
scripting (XSS) attacks, as it can be used to inject potentially unsafe
strings provided by a user into the DOM.
While the property does prevent \f[CR]<script>\f[R] elements from
executing when they are injected, it is susceptible to many other ways
that attackers can craft HTML to run malicious JavaScript.
For example, the following example would execute the code in the
\f[CR]error\f[R] event handler, because the \f[CR]<img>\f[R]
\f[CR]src\f[R] value is not a valid image URL:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] name = \(dq<img src=\(aqx\(aq onerror=\(aqalert(1)\(aq>\(dq;
element.outerHTML = name; \f[I]// shows the alert\f[R]
.EE
.PP
You can mitigate these issues by always assigning \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R]
objects instead of strings, and enforcing trusted types using the
\f[CR]require\-trusted\-types\-for\f[R] CSP directive.
This ensures that the input is passed through a transformation function,
which has the chance to sanitize the input to remove potentially
dangerous markup before it is injected.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Getting the serialization of an element
Reading \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] causes the user agent to serialize the
element.
.PP
Given the following HTML:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]div\f[R] id=\(dqexample\(dq>
  <\f[B]p\f[R]>Content</\f[B]p\f[R]>
  <\f[B]p\f[R]>Further Elaborated</\f[B]p\f[R]>
</\f[B]div\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
You can get and log the markup for the \f[CR]<div>\f[R] as shown:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] myElement = document.querySelector(\(dq#example\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] contents = myElement.outerHTML;
console.log(contents);
\f[I]// \(aq<div id=\(dqexample\(dq>\(rsn  <p>Content</p>\(rsn  <p>Further Elaborated</p>\(rsn</div>\(aq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Replacing the element
In this example we\(cqll replace an element in the DOM by assigning HTML
to the element\(cqs \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] property.
To mitigate the risk of XSS, we\(cqll first create a
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] object from the string containing the HTML, and
then assign that object to \f[CR]outerHTML\f[R].
.PP
Trusted types are not yet supported on all browsers, so first we define
the trusted types tinyfill.
This acts as a transparent replacement for the Trusted Types JavaScript
API:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]if\f[R] (\f[B]typeof\f[R] trustedTypes === \(dqundefined\(dq)
  trustedTypes = { createPolicy: (n, rules) \f[B]=>\f[R] rules };
.EE
.PP
Next we create a \f[CR]TrustedTypePolicy\f[R] that defines a
\f[CR]createHTML()\f[R] for transforming an input string into
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] instances.
Commonly implementations of \f[CR]createHTML()\f[R] use a library such
as \c
.UR https://github.com/cure53/DOMPurify
DOMPurify
.UE \c
\ to sanitize the input as shown below:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] policy = trustedTypes.createPolicy(\(dqmy\-policy\(dq, {
  createHTML: (input) \f[B]=>\f[R] DOMPurify.sanitize(input),
});
.EE
.PP
Then we use this \f[CR]policy\f[R] object to create a
\f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] object from the potentially unsafe input string,
and assign the result to the element:
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// The potentially malicious string\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] untrustedString = \(dq<p>I might be XSS</p><img src=\(aqx\(aq onerror=\(aqalert(1)\(aq>\(dq;

\f[I]// Create a TrustedHTML instance using the policy\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] trustedHTML = policy.createHTML(untrustedString);

\f[I]// Inject the TrustedHTML (which contains a trusted string)\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] element = document.querySelector(\(dq#container\(dq);
element.outerHTML = trustedHTML; \f[I]// Replaces the element with id \(dqcontainer\(dq\f[R]

\f[I]// Note that the  #container div is no longer part of the document tree,\f[R]
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] While you can directly assign a string to
\f[CR]outerHTML\f[R] this is a security risk if the string to be
inserted might contain potentially malicious content.
You should use \f[CR]TrustedHTML\f[R] to ensure that the content is
sanitized before it is inserted, and you should set a CSP header to
enforce trusted types.
.RE
.SH SEE ALSO
.IP \(bu 2
Serializing DOM trees into XML strings: \f[CR]XMLSerializer\f[R]
